{
  "texts": [
    "Public blockchains, like Bitcoin and Ethereum [14,15], allow anyone to join without restrictions.",
    "In contrast, permissioned blockchains (also known as private blockchains) restrict access to known participants.",
    "The characteristics of blockchain networks may differ between these two types.",
    "Public blockchains are often more complex due to their openness, necessitating careful design and consensus mechanisms that may impact scalability and performance.",
    "Additionally, public blockchains may not be suitable for sharing sensitive information, such as enterprise data, as shared records are visible to all participants [16]."
  ]
}